My brother Adrián, taken shortly before he passed in Tijuana, MX, 2007.

Adrián passed away before smartphones and phone cameras were a thing, and the lack of documentation of his life is the reason I became a photographer, and more specifically, why I only make portraits. All the joy, the people I’ve met, and opportunities I’ve experienced because of my work, I owe to him. He is survived by my now 16 year-old gorgeous and talented niece who makes an appearance in this image. 

Today would’ve been his 38th birthday. 
Happy birthday big bro!

Motion portrait of Doctor Mike. New York, NY.

I first met Mike very briefly at a movie premiere in New York back in 2019, though we didn’t really connect until the following year when the world was on pause. 
Our first photo session took place at his apartment, and consisted mostly of movie and video game talk (two of my favorites), followed by a solid cocktail, which he made from scratch and I drank on an empty stomach and proceeded to die.

I’ll get straight to the point: I’ve been struggling for some time. Months. Years. I’ve been going through what I consider to be an identity crisis, both personally and artistically.

If you’ve been following me for some time, you’ve noticed I’m constantly traveling to make work. It’s a privilege, no doubt, but one that comes at the cost of so many things in my personal life: relationships, a sense of home, among others. To some, I appear to be successful because of the people I’ve photographed, or the places I live, and this has only added to my frustration of why I don’t ever feel satisfied. Worthy, even? Imposter syndrome at its finest.

This thought sometimes extrapolates to the work itself. Though I don’t believe my process is ever superficial, I begin to see the purpose of it as materialistic, at times. While there’s nothing innately wrong with that (work is work and we got to pay rent and mortgages and life is stupid expensive in general), it does makes me question what I’m doing with my voice, if anything. 

One thing is clear to me: as I evolve as a person, the work naturally does, as well. 
What I evolve into, I’m not sure. I think I’m beginning to find some peace in the chaos; to accept it rather than fight it. Perhaps my purpose all this time has been to tell other people’s stories, and in the telling of those stories, lies mine; like a puzzle waiting to be put together by the viewer. This comforts me.

Now, I am constantly thinking about what I truly care about, what I want for my person, and what I want to say with my work; an essential question to answer if you’re an artist of any kind, really. I’ve been photographing my family and friends consistently again for the first time in a decade, and it’s the amongst the most meaningful work I’ve ever made. It likely won’t appear in Vogue, but they’re images that have immense value to me and mine, and it’s the kind of work I’d like to be remembered by. 

I’d love to hear from y’all, especially creatives. Do you question the work? Your part in the whole? What’re your thoughts? 
#photographyreels #portraitphotography #artiststruggles #photoartist

Friends & family lately. 
Images taken in New York, San Diego, Mexico City, Rosarito and Tijuana, MX. 

Like most portrait photographers, I started out by photographing and documenting my friends and family. It was the best (and cheapest - i.e. free 😂) way to learn and explore camera and light. 

Nobody, myself included, could have suspected I would end up dedicating my life to documenting people; mostly strangers, even. This past year has taken me full circle by going back to my roots in the medium; just older and a little wiser hopefully. 

When in the doubt, go back to the beginning y’all. 
#portraitphotography #profotoa2 #profotoglobal #portraitphotographer #hasselblad

Share if you relate! I’m assuming this happens to a lot of creatives out there with their art. I do wish I could be more verbal in my expression, but I hope my friends and family know this about me by now 😅. #photographyreels #lovelanguage #portraitphotography #artislove

Después naturalmente se obsesionó conmigo e hicimos imágenes juntos. 🍷
Feliz cumpleaños señor! 

@chuinavarro #motionportrait #photographyreels #retrato #reik #profotob10

Ok, so I’m 33 today. Just wanted to say how grateful I am for everything I have and everything I don’t. 32 was a year of tremendous evolution for me, both personally and in the work, and I’m feeling the best I’ve ever felt, as evidenced by me sharing a photo of myself with very little sleep and not caring 🤣. 

Also, to celebrate, I’ve shared MY ENTIRE PHOTO GEAR KIT, as well as created different kits for anyone who may be interested in exploring photography from scratch, or those interested in beginning to experiment with studio, or even those of you are comfortable and just want to up your equipment game for portraiture. You can find all 4 kits in the link on my bio 😊. 

Be grateful. Be kind. 

Image by the genius of @aaronjayyoung in his studio. Such an honor! 
#portraitphotography #portraitphotographer #photogear

My bff/roomie/sister/muse Andrea Barrón throughout the years. 

Ever since I started exploring photography, I’ve been taking portraits of this gal. In a way, every visually creative phase I’ve had is documented with the images we’ve made over the last 15 years, though we’ve been best friends for 20 now. These are just a few of my favorites. 
 
We were born in the same week in different countries, and we were bound to each other then without knowing. 
Happy bday, my Grace. 
@andreitabarron #portraitphotography #profotoglobal #profoto #friendsportrait

Mi hermano y mi padre en su despacho de contadores, Tijuana, MX. 

Pueden ver más del proceso y la historia en mis reels! 
You can check out more about the story behind these images in my reels! 

Crecí yendo a esta oficina a visitar a mi padre; hacía mi tarea y veía Plaza Sésamo mientras él trabajaba. Hace poco, mi hermano Alonso se convirtió en el director del despacho y ocupó la oficina que era de mi padre. Tenia años sin ir, y cuando visité a mi hermano y lo vi sentado en la silla que alguna vez fue de mi padre, me trajo mucha nostalgia e inspiración y NECESITABA hacer estas imágenes que contaran un poco de la historia de mi relación con ese espacio y los que la habitan.

#portraitphotography #familyphotojournalism #hasselblad #profotoa2 #profotoglobal #hasselbladx1dii

Mi hermanos, cuñada y la mayoría de mis sobrinos y yo visitamos a mi madre para su cumpleaños hace poco. 
A principios de este año, se fue a vivir a un pueblo en la quinta fregada del sur de los United y fue toda una aventura llegar, y valió toda la pena del mundo. Pasar esos días allá con todxs fue de los viajes más bellos que he tenido, y poder documentarlo siempre es un privilegio. 
My mayor tip para fotografxs siempre será ese: documenten a sus seres queridxs. 
Te amamos, madre 🫰🏼

Coming Out Stories, 2016-2019. 
For National Coming Out Day!
Check out the Behind The Image for more images and the full story behind this photo series! @_comingoutstories_ 

1)"I told a friend that I was gay, and she said: 'I'm a lesbian!'". Ricardo, came out at age 14. Mexico City, MX.
2) Diana, came out at age 22. Orange County, CA.
3 & 4) "When I left home, my mom told me not to get anyone pregnant. I laughed, and she turned to me and asked: "You're gay, aren't you?'". Paco, came out at age 19. Mexico City, MX.
5) Alan Rowe, came out at age 8. Wharton, NJ.
6) "My mom walked in on my boyfriend and I in bed together". Cesar, came out at age 18. Mexico City, MX.
7 & 8) "It was my first drag performance and my family was in the audience. I was terrified, but when it was over I saw them applaud. Sonnata, came out at age 19. Veracruz, MX. 
9) Bart, came out at age 21. Queens, NY. 
10) Cole, came out at age 16. Litchfield, ME. 

#nationalcomingoutday #portraitphotography #comingout #comingoutday #hasselblad #profotoglobal

3 Razones por las cuales NO IMPORTA qué cámara uses:

1. La cámara es solo una herramienta. En teoría, deberías poder tomar la misma foto con cualquier cámara (con sensores de similar tamaño cuando mucho). De hecho, una de mis fotos favoritas que tomé este año fue tomada con mi celular. Así que puedes quedarte tranquilx con la marca en la que ya invertiste! 👍🏼 

2. La iluminación tiene mucho más impacto en la calidad visual que la cámara y el lente. No inviertas más en cámaras hasta no entender MUY bien cómo te gusta iluminar tus imágenes. 

3. Aunque quizá unas cámaras tengan más beneficios que otras (velocidad, rango dinámico, etc), al final lo que importa es si pudiste expresar lo que querías o contar la historia de tu foto exitosamente. DE NADA TE SIRVE UNA CÁMARA CARÍSIMA DE PARIS SI NO TIENES NADA QUE DECIR EN TUS IMÁGENES. 
___________________________

3 reasons why IT DOES NOT MATTER which camera you use:

1. The camera is just a tool. In theory, you should be able to take the same photo with any camera (with similar sensor size, if anything). In fact, one of my favorite images I made this year was taken with my phone. So feel free to stick with the brand you’re already invested in! 👍🏼 

2. Lighting has much more impact on visual quality than the camera and the lens. Don't invest in more expensive camera gear until you thoroughly understand how you like to light your images.

3. Although some cameras may have more benefits than others (speed, dynamic range, etc.), in the end, what matters is if you could express what you wanted or tell the story of your photo successfully. Having a stupid expensive camera is of no use if you have nothing to say in your images.

Enero 21
Tijuana, MX

Me desperté con la noticia de que Joseph Sinclair, ícono de la fotografía y amigo, había fallecido. De manera repentina y aleatoria. Mientras maniobraba entre el shock y la negación esta mañana, comencé a reflexionar, como uno suele hacer. Cuando me vaya, me gustaría ser recordado por mis imágenes. Por la gente en las historias que conté. Encontrarás un poco de mí en cada uno de ellxs. Mi vida nunca ha sido realmente sobre mí o para mí, a pesar de lo que dice mi terapeuta, y tendría razón en el caso de la mayoría de las personas. Pero hay algunxs de nosotrxs que simplemente sabemos. Joseph hacía que la gente se sintiera poderosa y hermosa, y el mundo es mejor ahora porque compartió su arte con nosotros. Gracias, Joe.

Ale
